Targeting a Housing Subsidy

Akira Di Sandro

2023-11-03

Introduction

The Department of Housing and Community Development (HCD) of Emil City runs a home repair tax credit program every year which a subset of home owners qualify for. About 25% of the people who enroll in the program end up taking the tax credit ($5,000) and see an average premium of $10,000 as a result of the home repairs done using the credit. In addition, the homes surrounding the repaired home see an aggregate premium of $56,000.

Motivation

Up until this point, the HCD has been advertising this program to home owners that qualify in a random manner, but this is an inefficient use of resources. Each person that enrolls in this program costs the HCD an average of $2850 for marketing and counselling costs. From prior data exploration, we’ve seen that certain characteristics of home owners, how and when they were contacted, and other economic variables correlate. We believe that we can build a model to predict which owners are most likely to enter the program and take the tax credit, allowing the HCD to advertise the program more effectively and ultimately saving some costs.

In this document, we present a model that we believe could help the HCD spend their money more efficiently.

subsidy <- read_csv("/Users/akidi/Documents/MUSA5080/Assignments/HW05/housingSubsidy.csv") %>% dplyr::select(-1)

Methods

Data Exploration

The first step is always to look at what our data looks like and understand how the features relate with program enrollment. This gives us an idea of which features have the most influence on whether someone decides to enroll in the program or not, along with what kind of features we can create from the data we have to improve our prediction model.

Logistic Regression

Once we have an idea of what features to include, we finalize a prediction model. In this case, the outcome we’re trying to predict is a binary (yes or no) one, so the best model to use. This type of model fits an S-shaped curve to our data and requires the analyst to figure out the best value for a threshold. Any point on the S-shaped curve above the threshold will be predicted to be an outcome of 1 (in our case, “yes” to the question, “Will this person enroll in the program?”), while anything below will be predicted to be an outcome of 0 (in our case, “no”). More details will be disclosed as they become relevant in this document.

Goodness of Fit and Cross Validation

We split the data into a training and testing set and train our model with the training set (65% of data). Using the prediction model, we predict the program enrollment status of the people in the testing set. We use various goodness of fit metrics including the McFadden R-squared value, sensitivity, specificity, and a Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve to assess our model’s ability to accurately predict program enrollment.

Using k-fold cross validation with 100 folds, we test the generalizability of the model. More specifically, we assess the generalizability by looking at the distributions of the measures, Area Under the Curve AUC (labeled as ROC) which is another goodness of fit metric, sensitivity, and specificity. Ideally, we have distributions that are close to the mean, which would mean our model generalizes to many subsets of data pretty consistently.

If we have poor goodness of fit metrics and/or cross validation we go back to the drawing board and test new models until we have one that is satisfactory.

Results

Understanding the Data

We first explore the data, specifically how the various features are related to program enrollment.

In figure 1, we see that the correlation between this subset of features (continuous) and program enrollment is generally weak (ranging from 0.05 to 0.35 for the absolute value of the correlation coefficient). The points at the top (y = 1) mean that those people did enroll in the program, while the points below (y = 0) means that they did NOT enroll. In the middle of the figure, we see that as people are less likely to enroll in the program the higher the inflation rate is. This makes sens because the $5000 credit can buy more things when the inflation rate is low, making the program look more attractive.

Prediction Model

For the following sections we present the Kitchen Sink model (a model with all data available used as predictors of outcome) side by side with our new prediction model to discuss the validity and efficiency of the latter model.

The Kitchen Sink model gives us an idea of which predictors are significant, or have a strong influence on whether a person enrolls in the program or not. From this information, we engineered some new features to include in a new and improved model. After defining and testing combinations of several new features, the best set of new features were (1) a binary variable describing whether the inflation rate was over 3 or not (1 and 0, respectively); (2) a 3-level categorical variable describing how much the homeowner spent on home repairs (repair costs < $5,075 = “low”, repair costs >= $5,075 and < $5,175 = “mid”, repair costs >= $5,175 = “high”); (3) a 3-level categorical variable describing the unemployment rate (unemployment rate < -2 = “very_negative”, unemployment rate >= -2 and < 0 = “negative”, unemployment rate >= 0 = “positive”); and (4) a binary variable describing whether pdays (number of days after individual was last contacted from a previous program) was > 250 or not (1 and 0, respectively).

Figure 5 summarizes these features’ relationships to program enrollment using counts. One notable relationship we can observe from this figure is that homeowners who spend the least amount on home repairs tend to enroll in the program more. Perhaps this can be explained by the fact that people who spend less money on home repairs tend to be thrifty and cost-efficient with their home improvements so they see the tax credit program as being veery attractive (another way to save money while improving the quality of their home).

Cross Validation

We performed a 100-fold cross validation for both the Kitchen Sink and New models. Figure 6 below summarizes the results of this cross validation by presenting the distribution of goodness-of-fit measures, specifically AUC, sensitivity (Sens), and specificity (Spec). According to these measures, the new model performs very similarly to the kitchen sink model. The distribution of these measures remains consistent across the two models, but the mean sensitivity and specificity values are slightly higher for the new model with a mean specificity of 0.980 and 0.981 as well as a mean sensitivity of 0.223 and 0.224 for the kitchen sink and new model respectively.

ctrl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 100, classProbs=TRUE, summaryFunction=twoClassSummary)

kitchcvFit <- train(y ~ ., data = subsidy %>%
                                  dplyr::select(
                                   -c(y_numeric)), 
                method="glm", family="binomial",
                metric="ROC", trControl = ctrl)

ROC Curve

We use a ROC curve to visualize the trade-off of TP and FP, two very important confusion metrics. The grey line in figure 7 represents the ratio of TP and FP for a model that performs as well as a coin-flip, being right 50% of the time and wrong the other 50% of the time. Our model’s TP/FP tradeoff is shown by the maroon-colored curve. Our model has an area under the curve (AUC) of 0.7976, which is a reasonable value for this goodness-of-fit metric.

ggplot(testProbs, aes(d = as.numeric(testProbs$Outcome), m = Probs)) +
  geom_roc(n.cuts = 50, labels = FALSE, colour = "#7a0728") +
  style_roc(theme = theme_grey) +
  geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0, size = 1.5, color = 'grey') +
  labs(title = "ROC Curve - New Model",
       caption = "Figure 7.") +
  theme_minimal()

# AUC
mod_AUC <- pROC::auc(testProbs$Outcome, testProbs$Probs) #0.7976

Cost Benefit Analysis

Now, we perform a cost benefit analysis for our model. As a reminder, the HCD will allocate an average of $2,850 per homeowner for marketing, phone calls, counseling sessions etc. as a way to persuade the homeowner to enroll in the credit program. Out of the homeowners who join the program, we estimate that 25% of them end up taking the $5,000 credit. For each homeowner who takes the credit sees an average of a $10,000 premium on their house sale and an average neighborhood aggregate premium of $56,000 for homes surrounding the one that received the home repair credit.

This means that for each person that we predict would enroll in the program that does actually enroll (true positives, TP), we initially allocate an average of $2,850. Out of these homeowners, 25% will take the tax credit. Let’s say we correctly predicted \(x\) homeowners to enroll, then the cost for TP would be \(\$2,850 x + \$5,000x\times0.25 = \$4,100x\). On the other hand, for each homeowner we correctly predict to enroll in the program, 25% would take the credit and see an average $10,000 premium on their house sale and a $56,000 premium for neighboring houses, so the benefit would be \(0.25x(\$10,000+\$56,000) = \$16,500x\). Thus, the total revenue for each TP would be \(\$16,500x - \$4,100x = \$12,400\).

In the case that we correctly predicted that the homeowner would not enroll in the program (true negatives, TN), no money would be allocated for the marketing of the program and we would see no benefit from this either (assuming that all the TN wouldn’t take the tax credit). Therefore, the total revenue for each TN would be $0.

If we incorrectly predicted that a homeowner would enroll in the program (false positive, FP), we would initially allocate $2,850 for each person. No tax credit is allocated for these homeowners and we do not see any of the premiums we previously talked about on their house sales. Therefore with a $0 benefit, we see an overall revenue of -$2,850 for each FP.

Lastly, for all of the homeowners that we incorrectly predicted would not enroll in the program (false negatives, FN), we would not allocate any money, so this would cost us $0. Though they end up enrolling in the program, they enrolled due to reasons unrelated to the marketing campaign, so we assume that the benefit from these homeowners is also $0, resulting in a total revenue of $0.

Table 2 summarizes the above information in addition to providing the count of TP, TN, FP, and FN as well as the total revenue we see from these groups. Though our rate of TP was relatively low (sensitivity of 0.229), the amount of revenue we see from this subset of homeowners is a hefty $446,400. This outweighs the revenue loss of $62,700 from the false positives. All in all, if implemented, this model (based on a 50% threshold) brings in a net revenue of $383,700.

# table describing what TP, TN, FP, FN mean along with count and revenue
cost_benefit_table <-
   testProbs %>%
      count(predOutcome, Outcome) %>%
      summarize(`True Negative` = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==0]),
                `True Positive` = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==1]),
                `False Negative` = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==1]),
                `False Positive` = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==0])) %>%
       gather(Variable, Count) %>%
       mutate(Revenue =
               case_when(Variable == "True Negative"  ~ 0,
                         Variable == "True Positive"  ~ (-2850*Count + .25*(-5000+66000)*Count),
                         Variable == "False Negative" ~ 0,
                         Variable == "False Positive" ~ -2850*Count)) %>%
    bind_cols(data.frame(Description = c(
              "We predicted no program enrollment and the homeowner did not enroll",
              "We predicted program enrollment and the homeowner enrolled",
              "We predicted no program enrollment but the homeowner did enroll",
              "We predicted program enrollment, but homeowner did not enroll")))

  kable_styling("striped", full_width = F) %>%

A unique aspect of using a logistic model is that we predict our outcome differently depending on how we set the threshold. Fiigure 8 visualizes the cost-benefit analysis by looking at the revenue by confusion matrix type for each 0.01 increment increase in threshold value. When we set the threshold to be vrey close to zero, we see about $2,000,000 in revenue from the TP, but at the same time we would be losing about $4,000,000 due to the FP. At first glance, it looks like the optimum threshold level is between 0.13-0.37.

caret::confusionMatrix(testProbs$predOutcome, testProbs$Outcome, 
                       positive = "1")

whichThreshold <- 
  iterateThresholds(
     data=testProbs, observedClass = Outcome, predictedProbs = Probs)
whichThreshold <- 
  whichThreshold %>%
    dplyr::select(starts_with("Count"), Threshold) %>%
    gather(Variable, Count, -Threshold) %>%
    mutate(Revenue =
             case_when(Variable == "Count_TN"  ~ 0,
                       Variable == "Count_TP"  ~ (-2850*Count + .25*(-5000+66000)*Count),
                       Variable == "Count_FN"  ~ 0,
                       Variable == "Count_FP"  ~ -2850*Count))

In order to decide the optimum value for the threshold for our model, we plot the total revenue and total count of credits (defined as a quarter of the homeowners in the TP group) allocated for each potential value of threshold. As we seen in figure 9, a threshold of 0.12 seems to bring in the most amount of total revenue.

whichThreshold_rev <- whichThreshold %>% 
  mutate(credit_count = ifelse(Variable == "Count_TP", Count/4,0)) %>% 
  group_by(Threshold) %>% summarise(total_rev = sum(Revenue),
                                    total_credits = sum(credit_count))

whichThreshold_rev %>% 
  dplyr::select(Threshold, total_rev, total_credits) %>%
  rename(`Total Revenue` = total_rev,
         `Total Count of Credits` = total_credits) %>% 
  gather(Variable, Value, -Threshold) %>%
  ggplot(aes(Threshold, Value, colour = Variable)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_vline(xintercept = pull(arrange(whichThreshold_rev, -total_rev)[1,1])) +
    scale_colour_manual(values = mypalette1) +
    facet_wrap(~Variable, scales = "free") +
    plotTheme() + 
    labs(title = "Total Revenue and Counts of Credit by Threshold",
         subtitle = "Vertical line denotes optimal threshold",
         caption = "Figure 9.")

opt_thresh <- pull(arrange(whichThreshold_rev, -total_rev)[1,1])

Compared to the default threshold of 50% that we were using to predict the outcomes from our model in our analyses above, using a 12% threshold would lead to a much higher total revenue and count of credits. We would see an increase of 197% in total revenue as well as a 278% increase in total counts of credits (as shown in table 3).

Conclusion

In conclusion, this model is not ready for deployment. Though we engineered a few useful features, our new model performs better than the kitchen sink model by a very small amount. We clearly are not capturing some features or patterns in the data that help us understand what convinces people to sign up for this tax credit program. More feature engineering and data exploration could make this better, but perhaps the dataset that we started with doesn’t tell the whole story. Our model may benefit from incorporating data from outside data sources such as the US Census data. This could help us link homeowners to neighborhood median income, racial make-up of neighborhoods, along with other features that may explain what other factors make a homeowner more likely to enroll in this kind of program.

Once we have a better understanding of the factors that make homeowners want to enroll in these programs, not only can we target those who fit the criteria of homeowners who are most likely to enroll in the program, but also we can include keywords that can immediately capture homeowners’ attention. We would use what we understand about factors that correlate to program enrollment as keywords in order to more quickly and strongly convince homeowners that they should enroll in the program.
